          header
"><figure class="media-object-image img-header"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="860" height="573" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-823784?width=860&amp;height=573" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Twitter&#39;s new logo is seen projected on the corporate headquarters building in downtown San Francisco.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: CARLOS BARRIA/REUTERS </p></figcaption></figure></div></div></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001084213"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline"> By <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/suzanne-vranica" itemprop="url" rel="author">Suzanne Vranica</a></span> and <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/patience-haggin" itemprop="url" rel="author">Patience Haggin</a></span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1"> Updated July 25, 2023 5:39 pm ET </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/elon-musks-rebranded-twitter-cuts-ad-prices-d2615d8f"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><p> X Corp. is cutting ad prices as it tries to woo brands back to the <a href="https://www.wsj.com/topics/person/elon-musk">Elon Musk</a> -owned platform.</p><p> The <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/elon-musk-says-twitter-will-change-its-logo-to-x-5f73c349?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">social network formerly known as Twitter</a> is offering new incentives on certain ad formats in the US and UK and warning brands that they will lose their verified status unless they reach certain spending thresholds, emails sent this week to advertisers and viewed by The Wall Street Journal show.</p><p> The company, which makes most of its money from advertising, <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/elon-musk-twitter-advertisers-exodus-11671722594?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">has struggled to draw new ad commitments</a> under Musk&#39;s ownership in part because brands are concerned about Musk&#39;s approach to management and content moderation. The advertising industry is also in a slump, and several media companies have begun offering brands discounts.</p><p> X this week began offering some advertisers reduced pricing on video ads that run alongside a list of trending topics in X&#39;s “Explore” tab, according to emails viewed by the Journal. Such ads give brands 24-hour placement atop the site&#39;s list of trending topics.</p><p> It is offering 50% off any new bookings of those ads until July 31, among other discounts. “The goal of these discounts is to help our advertisers gain reach during crucial moments on Twitter such as the Women&#39;s World Cup,” one of the emails read. </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><div class="media-object-video"><div class="wsj-media-summary clearfix"><div class="strap-container"><h4 class="strap" itemprop="description"></h4></div></div><iframe width="400" height="225" src="https://video-api.wsj.com/api-video/player/v3/iframe.html?guid=0F91130A-ED9D-497B-A282-F26CCCF5DD91&amp;height=225&amp;width=400&amp;plid=video_amp&amp;chainVideos=true&amp;parentUrl=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.wsj.com%2Famp%2Farticles%2Felon-musks-rebranded-twitter-cuts-ad-prices-d2615d8f&amp;a=a" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe><p class="imageCaption"> Twitter&#39;s signature blue bird logo switched to an &#39;X&#39; for many users on Monday after the platform&#39;s owner, Elon Musk, made the announcement in a series of tweets. The change comes as Twitter rebrands. Photo: Alain Jocard/Agence France-Presse/Getty Images<span class="imageCredit">
        
        
        </span></p></div></div><p>X also warned advertisers that beginning Aug. 7, brands&#39; accounts will lose their verification—a gold check mark that indicates their account truly represents their brand—if they haven&#39;t spent at least $1,000 on ads in the previous 30 days or $6,000 on ads in the previous 180 days, according to the email.</p><p> Verification on the social media platform is important to many companies because they fear bad actors could impersonate and misrepresent their brand as some Twitter users did in the early weeks of Musk&#39;s ownership. In one notorious example, an account posed as <a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/LLY" class="company-name">Eli Lilly</a> and tweeted that the company would make insulin free. Twitter subsequently said it <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/twitter-begins-removing-legacy-check-marks-54df246a?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">improved safeguards against impersonation</a> .</p><p> Musk tweeted earlier this month that the company had seen a “~50% drop in advertising revenue” and had negative cash flow. He recently hired Linda Yaccarino, NBCUniversal&#39;s former head of advertising, as the company&#39;s chief executive to help bring brands back.</p><p> Musk has said the company could be <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/twitter-loses-second-safety-executive-within-days-1954a51e?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">cash-flow positive</a> soon. Twitter suffered years of losses before Musk&#39;s takeover and <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/elon-musk-explores-raising-up-to-3-billion-to-pay-off-twitter-debt-11674669412?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">took on billions in debt</a> as part of Musk&#39;s acquisition.</p><p> This isn&#39;t the first time the platform has tried to bolster its revenue by offering ad discounts. The company <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/twitter-offers-free-ads-to-brands-that-advertise-on-its-platform-11673654556?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">offered big ad incentives</a> around the Super Bowl, typically Twitter&#39;s biggest ad-revenue generator, the Journal reported earlier this year. </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="466" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-823788?width=700&amp;height=466" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Some ad buyers are hopeful that Linda Yaccarino will bring much needed stability to the platform.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: Slaven Vlasic/Getty Images</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> While some brands such as Mondelez International have <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/tucker-carlson-twitter-show-advertising-bce7b12c?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">returned to spending</a> on the platform, the Journal previously reported, many brands have remained on the sidelines, according to ad buyers.</p><p> Doug Rozen, CEO of Dentsu Media, Americas, said last month at a Journal event during the Cannes Lions ad festival that the agency&#39;s spending on Twitter was down about 70%.</p><p> Some ad buyers are hopeful that Yaccarino will bring much needed stability to the platform because she understands the importance of content moderation for advertisers. Yaccarino “is a known quantity in terms of understanding brands,” said Christina Hanson, CEO of ad-buying agency OMD USA during the Journal event.</p><p> Some advertisers say working with Twitter has been fraught at times. On July 1, the company <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/twitter-limits-number-of-posts-users-can-read-prompting-disruptions-for-some-15bc01cc?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">limited how many posts</a> users could read on Twitter, an effort Musk said was designed to block other companies from scraping the platform for data. The company said the change was temporary and eased the limits soon after enacting them.</p><p> The move quickly rippled into the advertising industry: Limiting tweet visibility meant fewer users saw ads, and ad prices rose. One agency saw its ad prices jump almost 15% during the change, according to an ad buyer.</p><p> Another ad buyer said it saw a decrease in engagement with its ads. The company said a few days later that the effects on advertising were minimal.</p><p class="articleTagLine"> —Alexa Corse contributed to this article.</p><p> Write to Suzanne Vranica at <a href="mailto:Suzanne.Vranica@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">Suzanne.Vranica@wsj.com</a> and Patience Haggin at <a href="mailto:patience.haggin@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">patience.haggin@wsj.com</a></p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Tue, 25 Jul 2023 21:39:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/elon-musks-rebranded-twitter-cuts-ad-prices-d2615d8f</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/elon-musks-rebranded-twitter-cuts-ad-prices-d2615d8f<author><![CDATA[Suzanne VranicaPatience Haggin]]></author><category> WSJ公司</category><category>kwexclusive</category><category> Advertising Services</category><category>广告/营销/公共关系</category><category>商业/消费者服务</category><category>Online Service Providers</category><category>营销服务</category><category>Media/Entertainment</category><category>社交媒体平台/工具</category><category>技术</category><category>营销</category><category>价格</category><category>Sales Promotions</category><category>广告</category><category>Branding</category><category>企业/行业新闻</category><category>Markets/Marketing</category><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>生活/生活方式</category><category>Social Media</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法激活过滤器</category><category>会展行业新闻过滤器</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category> marketing</category><category>价格</category><category>sales promotions</category><category>广告</category><category>branding</category><category>公司的</category><category>行业新闻</category><category>markets</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>活的</category><category>生活方式</category><category>social media</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法蒂瓦过滤器</category><category>会展行业新闻过滤器</category><category>advertising services</category><category>公共关系</category><category>商业</category><category>消费服务</category><category>online service providers</category><category>营销服务</category><category>媒体</category><category>娱乐</category><category>社交媒体平台</category><category>工具</category><category>技术</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[Verizon Says Tests of Lead Cable Sites Are Underway]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div> Old, incomplete records complicate cleanup-cost assessment, CFO says <!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001081843"><div class="is-lead-inset"><div class="media-object scope-
          header
"><figure class="media-object-image img-header"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="860" height="573" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-816690?width=860&amp;height=573" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Verizon 面临着来自无线和有线竞争对手的激烈竞争。</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: Victor J. Blue/Bloomberg News </p></figcaption></figure></div></div></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001081843"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline"> By <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/drew-fitzgerald" itemprop="url" rel="author">Drew FitzGerald</a></span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1"> Updated July 25, 2023 12:47 pm ET </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/verizon-vz-q2-earnings-report-2023-955fdc2e"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><p> <a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/VZ" class="company-name">Verizon Communications</a> said it is too soon to gauge how much it might cost to address lead-sheathed cables in the oldest parts of its network, a question that has dogged the telecom company as it focuses on growing its wireless business.</p><p> “There are a number of unknowns in this area, including whether there is a health risk presented by undisturbed lead-sheathed cable,” finance chief Tony Skiadas told investors Tuesday. “We do not believe there&#39;s a meaningful way to estimate any potential cost to the company or that any such estimate would even be useful.”</p><p> A Wall Street Journal investigation found that <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/lead-legacy-a266d59b?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">aging lead-clad telephone cables</a> still crisscross the country and could pose a potential health hazard in some areas. <a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/VZ" class="company-name">Verizon</a> said a third-party expert is testing its sites identified in the Journal&#39;s reporting but won&#39;t have results for several weeks.</p><p> Verizon has said lead-covered cables make up a small percentage of the less than 540,000 miles of cable in its copper network, though that figure excludes network pieces acquired from MCI and XO Communications. Skiadas said the company is still poring over those acquired companies&#39; historical records.</p><p> <a href="https://quotes.wsj.com/T">AT&amp;T</a> said last week that lead-clad lines make up less than 10% of the 2 million miles of sheathed copper cable in its network. <a href="https://quotes.wsj.com/T">AT&amp;T</a> Chief Executive John Stankey wrote in a note to employees that “the Journal&#39;s reporting conflicts with what independent experts have long stated about the safety of lead-clad telecom cables and our own environmental testing” and that the company would work with stakeholders to address any new safety concerns. The company is slated to report its second-quarter results Wednesday.</p><p> Both companies inherited a web of aging telephone lines from their predecessor companies but reap almost all of their profits from more modern fiber optics and cellphone connections.</p><h3>无线引擎</h3><p>Verizon added more prime wireless customers in the latest quarter but reported a decline in profit and revenue, a symptom of customers taking longer <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/time-to-upgrade-your-old-phone-more-consumers-say-not-yet-11661079600?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">to upgrade their old smartphones</a> .</p><p>这家美国用户数量最多的手机运营商在 6 月份季度结束时，其后付费电话连接数增加了 8,000 个，其不断增长的业务部门继续抵消了消费者部门萎缩的影响。投资者跟踪后付费客户群以及预付费电话和家庭互联网订阅的变化，以衡量电信公司的财务状况。</p><p>来自无线和有线竞争对手的激烈竞争给威瑞森最近的稳定利润蒙上了阴影。在过去一年半的大部分时间里，其消费者部门的客户流失，促使该公司<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/verizon-shakes-up-executive-team-after-tough-year-f28cbbc3?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">重组了其最高管理层</a>，并<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/verizon-overhauls-mobile-plans-to-make-them-less-confusing-8ff1e790?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">彻底改革了无线计划的营销方式</a>。</p><p> Total revenue fell 3.5% to $32.6 billion in the second quarter.</p><p> Verizon 表示，销量下滑主要是由于智能手机升级减少，随着用户使用设备的时间更长，这一趋势在整个行业持续存在。 Its core wireless service revenue rose 3.8% to $19.1 billion, fueled by wireless home internet growth, price increases and the reclassification of some fee revenue.</p><h3>底线</h3><p>Verizon 的整体利润从上年同期的 52 亿美元降至 46.5 亿美元。按每股计算，利润从 1.24 美元降至 1.10 美元，这一数字包括与裁员相关的遣散费以及其他费用。不包括一次性项目，利润强于分析师的预期。</p><p> “The steps that we have taken to improve our operational performance are working, and we are confident that we will achieve our financial targets for the full year,” Chief Executive</p> Hans Vestberg said in a news release.<p></p><h3>投资者反应</h3><p>Verizon shares rose about 1% in Tuesday trading.</p><p>由于收入增长疲弱和巨额债务负担令投资者感到不安，Verizon 及其竞争对手 AT&amp;T 的股价在过去一年中大幅下跌。随着美联储加息，派息股票也难以吸引投资者，此举催生了更多高收益投资争夺投资者的注意力。</p><p> Telecom stocks fell further in July after the Journal&#39;s investigation.最近几天，市场已经复苏，因为这些公司提供了有关仍在其网络中的线路的一些详细信息，使华尔街分析师能够完善对潜在清理成本的估计。 </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          inline
"><iframe width="300" height="300" src="https://graphics.wsj.com/dynamic-inset-iframer/?url=https://asset.wsj.net/wsjnewsgraphics/projects/narrator/d90969df-db3f-4890-9f4e-2892f502493a.json" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe></div><p>写信给德鲁·菲茨杰拉德 ( <a href="mailto:andrew.fitzgerald@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">andrew.fitzgerald@wsj.com)</a></p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Tue, 25 Jul 2023 16:47:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/verizon-vz-q2-earnings-report-2023-955fdc2e</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/verizon-vz-q2-earnings-report-2023-955fdc2e<author><![CDATA[Drew FitzGerald]]></author><category> WSJ公司</category><category>公司收益</category><category>Wires/Cables</category><category>电信服务</category><category>无线电信服务</category><category>Industrial Goods</category><category>财务绩效</category><category>Earnings</category><category>企业/行业新闻</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法激活过滤器</category><category>会展行业新闻过滤器</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>威瑞森通讯公司</category><category>维兹</category><category>美国电话电报公司</category><category>时间</category><category>financial performance</category><category>收益</category><category>公司的</category><category>行业新闻</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法蒂瓦过滤器</category><category>会展行业新闻过滤器</category><category>wires</category><category> cables</category><category>电信服务</category><category>无线电信服务</category><category>industrial goods </category></item><item><title><![CDATA[Stuck on a Flight? Know Your Rights During a Tarmac Delay]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div> If bad weather or plane congestion has you stranded on the runway, here are your rights as an airline passenger <figure><img src="https://images.wsj.net/im-821700/?width=2000&amp;size=1.5" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><figcaption> Illustration by Jon Krause <span>Illustration by Jon Krause</span> </figcaption></figure><!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001073822"></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001073822"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline"> By <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/allison-pohle" itemprop="url" rel="author">Allison Pohle</a></span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1"> Updated July 25, 2023 12:13 pm ET </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/tarmac-delay-rights-airports-9c5b1464"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          bigtophero
"></div><p> Unplanned time on the tarmac is becoming depressingly normal for US travelers this summer.</p><p> Federal data on tarmac delays lags behind three months, but veteran travelers say they have observed long waits on the tarmac at major airports across the country. In a typical tarmac delay, a plane either arrives and needs to wait for a gate or is awaiting takeoff after plane doors have closed.</p><p> <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/flight-cancellations-and-delays-mount-as-thunderstorms-hit-east-coast-c11c9161?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">Severe weather</a> has strained airlines&#39; operations and contributed to tarmac delays. The weather problems delay planes from taking off and lead to a shortage of available gates for arriving aircraft.</p><p> The delays have been noticeable at <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/united-airlines-newark-flights-cut-9f5f57f6?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">New York-area airports</a> . When weather worsens, departures and arrivals are more spaced out, says the Port Authority of New York and New Jersey, which operates the airports. Airline executives have also said a <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/faa-tries-to-ease-flight-congestion-at-new-york-airports-933d1da0?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">shortfall of air-traffic controllers</a> has exacerbated challenges.</p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          wrap
"></div><p> “No one is happy about airport delays, which is why we are working closely with our partners to reduce tarmac delays that have been overwhelmingly caused by a recent stretch of bad weather in both the New York/New Jersey region and at destination airports,” a Port Authority spokeswoman said in an email.</p><p> More than a decade ago, the Transportation Department implemented a rule prohibiting long tarmac delays. If airlines keep passengers on board for longer than DOT rules allow without the chance to deplane, they could face fines. That rule dramatically reduced the number of incidents when passengers were stranded on planes for several hours, aviation analysts say. But delays do still happen—the DOT <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/united-airlines-is-fined-1-9-million-for-runway-delays-11632516201?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">has fined airlines</a> for tarmac delays, including $1.9 million to <a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/UAL" class="company-name">United Airlines</a> in 2021.</p><p> A July 17 <a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/DAL" class="company-name">Delta Air Lines</a> flight from Las Vegas to Atlanta sat on the ground for about three hours while the temperature outside reached more than 110 degrees.</p><p> Tashina and Janssen Robinson were on the flight with their 16-year-old niece and 1-year-old baby. The Robinsons, who live in Atlanta, were flying home after a family reunion and said the air conditioners on the plane were turned on. But Tashina says the weak air stream felt like “blowing a fan in the sun.”</p><p> The Transportation Department is investigating the incident. Delta says it is complying with the investigation and is looking into what led to the uncomfortable temperatures onboard.</p><p> The DOT <a href="https://www.transportation.gov/individuals/aviation-consumer-protection/tarmac-delays" target="_blank" class="icon none">has consumer protections</a> in place for these situations, though they can be limited. Here is what to know about your rights during a tarmac delay. </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="444" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-822623?width=700&amp;height=444" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> DOT rules require airlines to start moving to a place where passengers can exit before the delay exceeds three hours for domestic flights and four hours for international flights, with some exceptions.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: Kena Betancur/Getty Images</p></figcaption></figure></div><h3> Why do planes get stuck on the tarmac?</h3><p> Weather that prevents aircraft from taking off is one of the main reasons for ground delays, says Michael McCormick, a former Federal Aviation Administration senior executive and assistant professor at Florida&#39;s Embry-Riddle Aeronautical University.</p><p> Passengers hundreds of miles from a storm system might experience a ground delay as air-traffic controllers work to reduce congestion in the area with bad weather. Severe and frequent thunderstorms cut off routes for aircraft, McCormick says. When flights can&#39;t take off, there aren&#39;t enough gates for arriving aircraft to park. Staffing or mechanical issues can also cause delays.</p><p> Limited runway capacity at New York&#39;s airports exacerbates weather and air-traffic control issues, says</p> Paul Hudson, president of FlyersRights, a consumer advocacy organization.<p></p><p> The Port Authority says it is making investments at its airports, including to airport taxiways, to help planes move faster on and off runways.</p><h3> Does my airline owe me compensation for a tarmac delay?</h3><p> No. But they must provide you with a snack and water no later than two hours after the start of the tarmac delay. They aren&#39;t required to serve meals even if the delay lasts a long time.</p><div class="media-object scope-web
          wrap
"><div class="media-object-rich-text"><h4>分享你的意见</h4><p><em>What has been your experience this summer with air travel?加入下面的对话。</em></p></div></div><p> Airlines are required to provide working toilets, comfortable cabin temperatures and medical attention to those who might need it. There is no set temperature defined as comfortable.</p><p> If your flight is delayed or canceled after a tarmac delay, you might be owed compensation. Some airlines give vouchers for food, hotels or ground transportation resulting from a delay or cancellation—so long as the delay or cancellation is in their control. (Weather-related issues don&#39;t apply.)</p><h3> How long can the airline keep passengers on the plane?</h3><p> For domestic flights, DOT rules require airlines to start moving to a place where passengers can exit before the delay exceeds three hours. This applies to both arrivals and departures. For international flights, the time limit is four hours. But it allows exceptions for safety, security and air-traffic control-related reasons.</p><p> For example, if your aircraft is number four for takeoff in a line of 30 planes, it could be considered a disruption to air-traffic operations to move out of line and return to the gate, says McCormick.</p><h3> What can I do if my plane is stuck on the tarmac?</h3><p> Your options are limited in the time before you have the chance to get off the plane. If you do choose to get off during the tarmac delay, the airline isn&#39;t required to let you back on and you might have to find another flight.</p><p> There is no guarantee you will be reunited with your bags once you deplane, McCormick says.</p><p> Planes are full these days, which means there is no guarantee you will get on the next flight out, Hudson says.</p><p> <em>This article may be updated</em> .</p><p> <em>Sign up for the new</em> <a href="https://www.wsj.com/newsletters?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none"><em>WSJ Travel newsletter</em></a> <em>for more tips and insights from the Journal&#39;s travel team.</em></p><p> Write to Allison Pohle at <a href="mailto:allison.pohle@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">allison.pohle@wsj.com</a></p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Tue, 25 Jul 2023 16:13:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/tarmac-delay-rights-airports-9c5b1464</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/tarmac-delay-rights-airports-9c5b1464<author><![CDATA[Allison Pohle]]></author><category> wsjlifework</category><category> Airlines</category><category> Passenger Airlines</category><category> Airports</category><category> Air Transport</category><category> Transportation/Logistics</category><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>运输</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category> United Airlines Holdings</category><category> UAL</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>运输</category><category>airlines</category><category> passenger airlines</category><category> airports</category><category> air transport</category><category> transportation</category><category> logistics </category></item><item><title><![CDATA[At Spotify, Podcast Cuts and Higher Music Royalties Deepen Losses]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>流媒体巨头图书用户增长创下有史以来最强劲的季度<!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001081300"><div class="is-lead-inset"><div class="media-object scope-
          header
"><figure class="media-object-image img-header"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="860" height="572" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-822523?width=860&amp;height=572" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> 6 月，喷火战机乐队 (Foo Fighters) 的戴夫·格罗尔 (Dave Grohl) 在 Spotify 在法国戛纳举办的活动中表演。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：安东尼·琼斯/盖蒂图片社</p></figcaption></figure></div></div></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001081300"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline">作者： <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/anne-steele" itemprop="url" rel="author">安妮·斯蒂尔</a></span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1">更新于 2023 年 7 月 25 日上午 11:07（东部时间） </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/spotify-spot-q2-earnings-report-2023-646fa771"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><p> Z 世代和海外听众帮助<a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/SPOT" class="company-name">Spotify</a>创造了有史以来最强劲的新用户季度业绩，而这家流媒体巨头则报告称，由于播客削减和音乐版税成本上升，损失更加严重。</p><p>这家音频公司正努力提高盈利能力，其中包括调整播客投资规模和提高价格。</p><p> On Monday, Spotify said it <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/spotify-plans-to-raise-price-of-premium-plan-in-u-s-77c3f360?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">is raising prices for its premium subscription</a> to $10.99 a month in the US from its longstanding price of $9.99, confirming an earlier report by The Wall Street Journal.该公司已告诉投资者，今年将提高价格，作为持续推动持续盈利的一部分。</p><p> Spotify shares fell 14.26% Tuesday after the company reported steeper losses from podcasting cuts and higher music royalty costs.</p><p>这家斯德哥尔摩流媒体巨头创下了有史以来最强劲的新用户季度业绩，但未达到收入目标，并且本季度的前景弱于预期。</p><p>这家音频巨头表示，很快将提高全球其他数十个市场的价格，包括英国、法国、墨西哥、秘鲁、新加坡和香港。</p><p>当被问及公司长期提价的能力时，首席执行官 Daniel Ek 表示，Spotify 将继续改进其产品、增加播客并扩大有声读物产品。 “如果我们这样做，我相信我们有能力提高价格，将性价比保持在适当的水平，”他说。</p><h3> Spotify 增加了多少新订阅者？</h3><ul class="articleList"><li>总体而言，该流媒体月活跃用户数为 5.51 亿，比去年同期增长 27%，比指导值高出 2100 万，创公司历史新高。该公司表示，这得益于成功的营销和提高的保留率。</li><li> Spotify 的付费用户数量（其最赚钱的客户类型）增长了 17%，达到 2.2 亿，比公司预期高出 300 万。</li><li>该公司表示，所有地区的用户增长均强于预期，尤其是拉丁美洲。该公司还增加了更多年轻的 Z 世代听众。 </li></ul><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><div class="media-object-video"><div class="wsj-media-summary clearfix"><div class="strap-container"><h4 class="strap" itemprop="description"></h4></div></div><iframe width="400" height="225" src="https://video-api.wsj.com/api-video/player/v3/iframe.html?guid=E91EB935-C3EE-42FF-B41A-246614F8F1A1&amp;height=225&amp;width=400&amp;plid=video_amp&amp;chainVideos=true&amp;parentUrl=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.wsj.com%2Famp%2Farticles%2Fspotify-spot-q2-earnings-report-2023-646fa771&amp;a=a" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe><p class="imageCaption"> Spotify 每月拥有 5 亿用户，是全球最大的音乐流媒体服务。以下是该平台如何使用机器学习技术生成个性化推荐的内部介绍。图片插图：Ryan Trefes<span class="imageCredit">
        
        
        </span></p></div></div><h3>公司盈利吗？</h3><ul class="articleList"><li>截至 6 月份的季度，该公司亏损 3.02 亿欧元，相当于约 3.35 亿美元，即每股 1.55 欧元，而上年同期亏损 1.25 亿欧元，即 85 欧分。由于与取消播客节目、裁员和超额房地产减值相关的 4400 万欧元费用，其毛利率下降至 24.1%。</li></ul><ul class="articleList"><li> Spotify 表示，该公司在此期间产生了更高的音乐版税成本，并且播客盈利能力有所改善。该季度结束后，它与主要唱片公司合作伙伴达成了新的许可协议，其中包括允许流媒体提高订阅价格。该公司将大约 70% 的收入支付给音乐版权持有者。</li><li> Ek 在接受采访时表示，新协议和公司提价是“Spotify 和音乐行业的双赢”。</li></ul><ul class="articleList"><li>多年来，高管们一直表示，随着 Spotify 试图吸引世界各地的用户并扩展到新的音频形式，该公司将优先考虑增长投资而不是利润。去年秋天，该公司表示，随着摆脱了大规模投资的时期，今年的盈利能力预计将有所改善。</li></ul><ul class="articleList"><li>自由现金流为 900 万欧元，衡量公司运营产生的现金，被许多投资者视为业绩的代表。而去年同期为 3700 万欧元，上一季度为 5700 万欧元。 </li></ul><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="467" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-822533?width=700&amp;height=467" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Spotify 将其在美国的高级订阅价格从每月 9.99 美元提高到每月 10.99 美元。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：Gabby Jones/彭博新闻</p></figcaption></figure></div><h3>收入呢？</h3><ul class="articleList"><li>第二季度总收入增长 11% 至 31.8 亿欧元，低于公司预期。</li><li>订阅收入是 Spotify 营收的最大贡献者，增长 11% 至 27.7 亿欧元。广告收入增长 12%，达到 4.04 亿欧元。广告收入对于 Spotify 播客业务的未来变得越来越重要，在第二季度占其总收入的近 13%。</li><li>本季度订阅业务的每位用户平均收入下滑 6% 至 4.27 欧元。由于 Spotify 通过折扣套餐和较低的价格在新兴市场吸引新用户，该指标有所下降。</li></ul><h3>其播客业务怎么样？</h3><ul class="articleList"><li> 6 月，Spotify 表示，由于播客业务盈利困难， <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/spotify-to-cut-200-jobs-as-it-reorganizes-podcasting-division-39720004?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">将裁员约 200 人</a>，即员工总数的 2%。该公司整合了一些顶级的 Gimlet 和 Parcast 工作室，并<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/meghan-markles-archetypes-podcast-at-spotify-wont-be-renewed-44311f4f?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">削减了许多原创</a>节目。</li><li> Ek 周二告诉投资者，四年前，在市场上还没有大量可用数据之前，该公司在播客上做出了“正确的选择”，而 Spotify 现在是该格式的顶级平台。 As it cuts costs, “we&#39;re coming at this with the process of right-sizing some deals, doubling down on some of the things that worked really nicely and then stepping out of some deals and relationships that hasn&#39;t worked out,” he said.</li></ul><ul class="articleList"><li> Spotify 还放松了对其部分播客的排他性安排，并开始将其分发到其他平台，此举旨在增加这些节目的受众和广告潜力。与乔·罗根、亚历克斯·库珀和​​艾玛·张伯伦等大牌明星的独家协议仍然有效。</li></ul><p><a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/NWSA" class="">新闻集团</a><span class="company-name-type">旗下的</span>道琼斯公司（《华尔街日报》的出版商）与 Spotify 的 Gimlet Media 部门建立了内容合作伙伴关系。</p><div class="media-object scope-web
          inline
